<div class="sub-content-header">Six Sessions to Round Out Your Four Days at CES</div>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<i><span class="smallText">Dec 23, 2010 11:58:15</span></i>

<br /><br />

If you don't have time to attend an entire track offered in the CES Conference Program, you may want to opt for these sponsored single sessions: 
<UL class=text>
<LI class=text><A href="http://www.cesweb.org/conferenceProgram/search/sessionDetails.asp?sessionid=4142">Femtocells —Living The Five Bar Lifestyle in the Digital Home, sponsored by Femto Forum</A><BR>Femtocells, the tiny home-based cell towers deployed by Sprint, AT&amp;T and Verizon, don't just spell the end of bad coverage. They provide the fastest mobile broadband experience and power a new generation of applications. The mobile handset will drive the digital home - controlling all your media and services.<BR></LI>
<LI class=text><A href="http://www.cesweb.org/conferenceProgram/search/sessionDetails.asp?sessionid=4164">Securing Network Architecture for the Connected World We Live In, sponsored by IPv6 Forum<BR></A>Connected Home, M2M, Smart Grid, Cloud, eHealthcare - each presumes interconnection between billions of devices on numerous networks. Cyber security attacks are increasingly predatory. Enterprise-centric security solutions are too costly and complex. IPv6 offers an inexpensive, scalable solution that can mitigate a range of attacks. And IPv6 can be deployed today.<BR></LI>
<LI class=text><A href="http://www.cesweb.org/conferenceProgram/search/sessionDetails.asp?sessionid=4123">Future of Wireless Devices on Airplanes, sponsored by Apex</A><BR>New technical developments can evolve further - for use on airplanes. Airlines today are offering passengers portable media players for inflight entertainment (IFE), allowing cell phone use, and working with vendors on other wireless devices. Join airline and IFE experts from the Airline Passenger Experience Association (APEX) to learn about technological advancements that will improve customer travel in the future. <BR></LI>
<LI class=text><A href="http://www.cesweb.org/conferenceProgram/search/sessionDetails.asp?sessionid=4134">How to Lighten the Energy Load From Electronics, sponsored by CNET</A> <BR>Gadgets and home electronics are becoming a bigger chunk of our electricity bills. What sorts of green technologies can you use to measure and keep your home power under control? What should people consider if they want to buy energy efficient and greener electronics? Join CNET editor Martin LaMonica as he and a panel of experts answer these hot questions.<BR></LI>
<LI class=text><A href="http://www.cesweb.org/conferenceProgram/search/sessionDetails.asp?sessionid=4163">Enhancing Driver Situational Awareness without Driver Distraction- IntelliDrive and Cooperative Vehicle Safety, sponsored by ITS America</A> <BR>Driver Distraction made major headlines the last two years. Industry responded with new technology solutions to reduce distraction risk. The US Department of Transportation responded by issuing guidance and jumpstarting cooperative crash avoidance technology deployment through their IntelliDrive program. In this session, industry and government will explore guidelines and solutions.<BR></LI>
<LI class=text><A href="http://www.cesweb.org/conferenceProgram/search/sessionDetails.asp?sessionid=4124">Connect2Car: Consumer's Lifestyle and the Transformation of Consumer Electronics in the Connected Vehicle, sponsored by SAE</A> <BR>Connected cars are the key to connected consumer lifestyles. The latest wave of built-in, brought-in and beamed-in devices are leading the way. Open innovation and collaboration are central to moving, making and growing consumer acceptance for the connected vehicle. The challenges for the automotive and consumer electronics industry stakeholders are to deliver on consumer's expectations of seamless interoperability.<BR></LI></UL>
<P class=text>&nbsp;</P>
<br><br>
