<div class="sub-content-header">Making the Home Connection</div>
&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;&nbsp;<i><span class="smallText">Dec 20, 2010 12:57:46</span></i>

<br /><br />

As a side-effect of the economy, consumers are enhancing and upgrading their stay-at-home experiences, especially as CE intersects with the kitchen. <BR><BR>Attractively styled high-def flat screens together with Internet connectivity, Blu-ray players and other components have taken the drag out of staying-at-home. People are experiencing the thrill of the movie theater in the comfort of a home theater or den. At some point, attention turns to munchies – and the kitchen. “What do we have to eat?”<BR><BR>The kitchen has always held a symbolic place at the center of the home. Most people fondly remember the smells of a Sunday dinner and the comfortable chitchat in the kitchen. For a while it seemed as if the kitchen got lost amidst the beauty of flat-screen TVs, videogame consoles and more – but now the kitchen is making a come-back. <BR><BR><A href="http://www.nxtbook.com/nxtbooks/cea/vision1110/#/10" target=_blank>Read the full story by Sue Schreine in the November/December 2010 issue of <EM>CE Vision Magazine.</EM></A><BR>
